173, 171, 169 Christopher Street, north side, between West and Washington Streets. No. 171 is the one-story frame shed in the center of the picture. In front of No. 173 stands the New York Public Library's Circulation Department truck, which travels about the Bronx. March 8, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

The same, three years later. The frame shed has been faced with tin; and the Volmer automobile agency has moved away from No. 169.

(1)
West Street, center and east side, from Christopher Street to West 10th (formerly Amos) Street, opposite Piers 44 to 45, North River, and east on the north side of Christopher Street towards Greenwich Street. The spires in the background are those of St. Veronica's Roman Catholic Church at 153-139 Christopher Street.
March 8, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A portion of the same, showing prominently Nos. 391 to 393 (right to left). No. 388, the 3-story brick, corner building and the adjoining 2½ structure have been demolished in this view. This row of buildings replaced the Weehawken Market that was built here about 1830 on a portion of the New York State Prison site. Weehawken Street (shown across vacant lot) was cut through at that time.
About 1937.

Gift of Dr. Michael Wishengrad, A.R.P.S.

Weehawken Street, west side, between Christopher and West 10th Street, showing the rear of the building bearing No. 393 West Street. This is popularly supposed to be the oldest structure in Manhattan. It rests on the site of the Weehawken Market, and which in turn succeeded to a portion of the old State Prison of 1797-1829. For further information, see, the New York Times of, Sunday, August 22, 1937. also : N.Y. Eve Post June 15, 1930.
About 1939

West Street, east side, south from Barrow to Morton St's., showing the block extending to Washington St. more or less cleared. Across the New York Central Railroad elevated roadbed (west side) appear loft structures on the east side of Washington Street. The 8 story building, No. 617-31 Washington St., is occupied by Bellas, Hess & Co. This utilizes the entire frontage from Barrow to Morton St's. At the S.E. corner of the latter thoroughfare, is the 9 story loft, No. 611-15 Washington St. identified with the Medical Supply Dept. of the U. S. Army.

May 7, 1940
No's. 1-2

P. L. Sperr
